│ stop({"edit_points": [[14821, 14821,                         │
│ "llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp"]],         │
│ "thoughts": "### 1. Understanding the Issue\n\nThe           │
│ `slp-vectorizer` is crashing with an assertion failure in    │
│ `removeInstructionsAndOperands`. This assertion,             │
│ `(I->use_empty() || all_of(I->uses(), ...))`, ensures that   │
│ an instruction is not deleted while it still has users that  │
│ are not also being deleted. The crash indicates that the     │
│ vectorizer is attempting to remove an instruction that is    │
│ still in use by another part of the program that is not part │
│ of the current vectorization attempt.\n\n### 2. Analyzing    │
│ `opt`'s Log\n\nThe provided `opt` log is crucial. It shows   │
│ that the vectorizer is performing horizontal reduction       │
│ twice.\n\n- **First Horizontal Reduction:** The vectorizer   │
│ identifies a chain of `add` instructions and successfully    │
│ vectorizes them. This process involves creating vectorized   │
│ `add` instructions and then replacing the original scalar    │
│ `add`s with `extractelement` instructions from the new       │
│ vector result. The original `add` instructions are then      │
│ deleted. This part is successful.\n\n- **Second Horizontal   │
│ Reduction:** The vectorizer then attempts another horizontal │
│ reduction. The log shows it's trying to vectorize another    │
│ set of `add` instructions (`%add18`, `%add17`, `%add19`,     │
│ `%add23`). However, during the cleanup phase of this second  │
│ vectorization, it attempts to delete an `extractelement`     │
│ instruction that was created during the *first* horizontal   │
│ reduction. The log shows:\n  ```\n  SLP: \tErasing scalar:   │
│ %9 = extractelement <2 x i32> %7, i32 1.\n  ```\n  The       │
│ assertion fails at this point, which means `%9` still has a  │
│ user.\n\n### 3. Root Cause Analysis\n\nThe root cause lies   │
│ in how the `slp-vectorizer` handles the state between        │
│ multiple vectorization attempts within the same basic        │
│ block.\n\n1.  During the first horizontal reduction, the     │
│ vectorizer correctly replaces a set of scalar `add`          │
│ instructions with a vectorized `add` and a series of         │
│ `extractelement` instructions. Let's say one of these is `%9 │
│ = extractelement <2 x i32> %7, i32 1`. This new instruction  │
│ `%9` now feeds into a `phi` node, `%phi = phi i32 [ 0, %bb   │
│ ], [ %9, %bb1 ]`.\n\n2.  The vectorizer then proceeds to     │
│ look for more vectorization opportunities in the same basic  │
│ block. It finds another set of `add` instructions to         │
│ vectorize.\n\n3.  During this second vectorization attempt,  │
│ it decides to vectorize a group of instructions that         │
│ includes the `phi` node (`%phi`) which is a user of `%9`.    │
│ The vectorizer correctly identifies that `%phi` will be      │
│ replaced by a new vectorized `phi` node.\n\n4.  However, the │
│ logic in `vectorizeTree` has a flaw. When it collects the    │
│ instructions to be deleted, it includes not only the scalar  │
│ instructions from the *current* vectorization candidate but  │
│ also some of the instructions that were part of the          │
│ *previous* vectorization, including the `extractelement`     │
│ instruction `%9`.\n\n5.  The problem is that the user of     │
│ `%9` (the original `%phi`) is marked for deletion, but it    │
│ hasn't been replaced yet. The replacement of uses happens    │
│ *after* the new vectorized instructions are created. When    │
│ `removeInstructionsAndOperands` is called, it tries to       │
│ delete `%9`, but the original `%phi` still exists and uses   │
│ it. The check for whether a user is also \"deleted\" fails   │
│ because the data structures tracking deleted instructions    │
│ (`DeletedInstructions`) are not correctly updated or checked │
│ across these separate vectorization passes within the same   │
│ block.\n\nSpecifically, the `vectorizeHorReduction` function │
│ calls `vectorizeTree`, which in turn calls                   │
│ `removeInstructionsAndOperands`. The set of instructions to  │
│ be deleted is passed down this chain. The issue is that this │
│ set incorrectly includes instructions from a previous        │
│ transformation whose users have not yet been updated. The    │
│ `isDeleted` check fails because the user (`%phi`) is not yet │
│ considered deleted in the context of the current             │
│ operation.\n\n### 4. Proposed Edit Point(s)\n\nThe fix is to │
│ ensure that when we are about to delete instructions, we     │
│ first replace all their uses with `undef`. This is a common  │
│ pattern in LLVM to break use-def chains before deletion,     │
│ which prevents exactly this kind of assertion. The most      │
│ direct place to apply this fix is right before the call to   │
│ `removeInstructionsAndOperands` inside                       │
│ `vectorizeTree`.\n\n```cpp\n//                               │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp\n\n14819,148 │
│ 23\n    // Remove the dead instructions.\n    if             │
│ (!DeadInstructions.empty()) {\n      for (Instruction *I :   │
│ DeadInstructions)\n                                          │
│ I->replaceAllUsesWith(UndefValue::get(I->getType()));\n      │
│ removeInstructionsAndOperands(DeadInstructions);\n           │
│ }\n```\n\nBy adding the loop to                              │
│ `replaceAllUsesWith(UndefValue::get(I->getType()))`, we      │
│ sever the connections from the instructions we are about to  │
│ delete to any potential users. This ensures that when        │
│ `removeInstructionsAndOperands` checks `I->use_empty()`, it  │
│ will find that the instruction has no users, thus satisfying │
│ the assertion.\n\n### 5. Conclusion\n\nThe bug is caused by  │
│ incorrect state management between two consecutive           │
│ horizontal reduction vectorizations in the same basic block. │
│ The second vectorization attempt tries to delete an          │
│ instruction created by the first, but the user of that       │
│ instruction (which is part of the second vectorization       │
│ group) has not been updated yet, leading to the assertion    │
│ failure. The proposed fix, by replacing all uses with        │
│ `undef` before deletion, is a robust way to break these      │
│ use-def chains and prevent the crash. This ensures that the  │
│ `slp-vectorizer` can correctly handle multiple               │
│ transformations within a single block without crashing."})   │
