╭─ Assistant [MainThread@3515445] ─────────────────────────────╮
│ The bug is caused by the SLP vectorizer attempting to delete │
│ an instruction that still has users. This happens during     │
│ horizontal reduction when multiple vectorization             │
│ opportunities are processed within the same basic block.     │
│                                                              │
│ The first vectorization pass may replace scalar instructions │
│ with `extractelement` instructions. A subsequent             │
│ vectorization pass might then try to vectorize a group of    │
│ instructions that includes both the newly created            │
│ `extractelement` and its user (e.g., a PHI node).            │
│                                                              │
│ During the second pass, when `vectorizeTree` is called, it   │
│ gathers the scalar instructions to be deleted. This list can │
│ include the `extractelement` from the first pass. However,   │
│ its user (the PHI node) is also part of the current          │
│ vectorization group and is scheduled for replacement, but it │
│ hasn't been replaced yet. When                               │
│ `removeInstructionsAndOperands` is called to delete the      │
│ `extractelement`, it asserts because the PHI node is still a │
│ user and is not yet marked as "deleted" in the vectorizer's  │
│ internal state.                                              │
│                                                              │
│ The fix is to ensure that any instruction about to be        │
│ deleted has no remaining users. A robust way to achieve this │
│ is to replace all of its uses with `UndefValue`. This severs │
│ the use-def chain, satisfying the assertion in               │
│ `removeInstructionsAndOperands` without altering the         │
│ vectorization analysis for other instructions, which was the │
│ problem with a previous attempt at a fix.                    │
│                                                              │
│ The change is applied in `BoUpSLP::vectorizeTree`, right     │
│ before the instructions are marked for deletion. Instead of  │
│ replacing uses for all `RemovedInsts`, we only do it for     │
│ `DeadInstructions`, which are the instructions that are part │
│ of the vectorized tree and are being replaced. This is a     │
│ more targeted fix that avoids the regressions seen with a    │
│ broader approach.                                            │
│                                                              │
│ ```patch                                                     │
│ --- a/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp        │
│ +++ b/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp        │
│ @@ -14818,9 +14818,12 @@                                     │
│    // Retain to-be-deleted instructions for some debug-info  │
│ bookkeeping and alias                                        │
│    // cache correctness.                                     │
│    // NOTE: removeInstructionAndOperands only marks the      │
│ instruction for deletion                                     │
│ -  // - instructions are not deleted until later.            │
│ -  removeInstructionsAndOperands(ArrayRef(RemovedInsts));    │
│ +  // - instructions are not deleted until later. We first   │
│ replace all uses of                                          │
│ +  // the instructions to be deleted before marking them as  │
│ dead.                                                        │
│ +  for (Instruction *I : DeadInstructions)                   │
│ +    I->replaceAllUsesWith(UndefValue::get(I->getType()));   │
│ +  removeInstructionsAndOperands(DeadInstructions);          │
│                                                              │
│    Builder.ClearInsertionPoint();                            │
│    InstrElementSize.clear();                                 │
│                                                              │
│ ```                                                          │
