│ The bug is a crash in the SLP vectorizer when processing a   │
│ specific pattern of horizontal reductions within a loop. The │
│ crash occurs because the vectorizer attempts to delete an    │
│ instruction that still has users. This situation arises from │
│ the interaction of multiple vectorization passes within the  │
│ same basic block.                                            │
│                                                              │
│ Here's a breakdown of the problem:                           │
│ 1.  The SLP vectorizer identifies a set of scalar            │
│ instructions for horizontal reduction and vectorizes them.   │
│ This process replaces the original scalar instructions with  │
│ a vector instruction followed by `extractelement`            │
│ instructions to get the scalar results.                      │
│ 2.  The vectorizer then continues to scan for more           │
│ vectorization opportunities in the same block. It finds      │
│ another candidate set for horizontal reduction.              │
│ 3.  This second set of candidates may include instructions   │
│ that use the results of the first vectorization pass (i.e.,  │
│ they use the `extractelement` instructions). For example, a  │
│ PHI node might be a user.                                    │
│ 4.  When vectorizing the second set, the vectorizer marks    │
│ both the new scalar candidates and their users (like the PHI │
│ node) for replacement. It collects all original scalar       │
│ instructions into a list of instructions to be deleted. This │
│ list can inadvertently include the `extractelement`          │
│ instruction from the first pass.                             │
│ 5.  The vectorizer then calls                                │
│ `removeInstructionsAndOperands` to delete these              │
│ instructions. However, at this point, the user of the        │
│ `extractelement` (the PHI node) has not yet been fully       │
│ replaced. It is only marked for replacement.                 │
│ 6.  `removeInstructionsAndOperands` asserts that an          │
│ instruction to be deleted must have no users, or all its     │
│ users must also be in the set of instructions being deleted. │
│ This assertion fails because the PHI node is still a valid   │
│ user and is not considered "deleted" yet by the internal     │
│ tracking mechanism for the current deletion operation,       │
│ leading to a crash.                                          │
│                                                              │
│ The fix is to explicitly sever the use-def chain for         │
│ instructions that are about to be deleted. By replacing all  │
│ uses of these instructions with an `undef` value, we ensure  │
│ they have no users when the deletion function is called.     │
│ This must be done carefully to avoid breaking debug          │
│ information, which also exists as users of these             │
│ instructions. Therefore, we only replace uses for            │
│ non-debug-info intrinsics.                                   │
│                                                              │
│ The change is applied in `BoUpSLP::vectorizeTree`, just      │
│ before the call to `removeInstructionsAndOperands`.          │
│                                                              │
│ ```patch                                                     │
│ --- a/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp        │
│ +++ b/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp        │
│ @@ -14818,9 +14818,13 @@                                     │
│    // Retain to-be-deleted instructions for some debug-info  │
│ bookkeeping and alias                                        │
│    // cache correctness.                                     │
│    // NOTE: removeInstructionAndOperands only marks the      │
│ instruction for deletion                                     │
│ -  // - instructions are not deleted until later.            │
│ +  // - instructions are not deleted until later. We first   │
│ replace all uses of                                          │
│ +  // the instructions to be deleted before marking them as  │
│ dead. This is to                                             │
│ +  // ensure that the instructions are not used by any other │
│ instruction that is                                          │
│ +  // not being deleted.                                     │
│ +  for (Instruction *I : RemovedInsts)                       │
│ +    I->replaceUsesWithIf(UndefValue::get(I->getType()),     │
│ +                         [](Use &U) { return                │
│ !isa<DbgInfoIntrinsic>(U.getUser()); });                     │
│    removeInstructionsAndOperands(ArrayRef(RemovedInsts));    │
│                                                              │
│    Builder.ClearInsertionPoint();                            │
│                                                              │
│ ```                                                          │
