│    removeInstructionsAndOperands(ArrayRef(RemovedInsts));    │
│                                                              │
│    Builder.ClearInsertionPoint();                            │
│                                                              │
│ ```The user is encountering a crash in the SLP Vectorizer.   │
│ The root cause is an assertion failure when the vectorizer   │
│ attempts to delete an instruction that still has users. This │
│ scenario occurs during horizontal reduction on a loop, where │
│ multiple vectorization passes are performed on the same      │
│ basic block.                                                 │
│                                                              │
│ An instruction created during one vectorization pass (e.g.,  │
│ an `extractelement`) can be a candidate for deletion in a    │
│ subsequent pass. However, its user (e.g., a PHI node which   │
│ is also part of the second vectorization group) might not be │
│ marked as "deleted" in the vectorizer's state at the exact   │
│ moment the deletion of the `extractelement` is attempted.    │
│ This leads to the assertion `trying to erase instruction     │
│ with users` being triggered.                                 │
│                                                              │
│ The most direct way to fix this is to sever the use-def      │
│ chain before attempting to delete the instruction. This can  │
│ be done by replacing all of its uses with an `undef` value.  │
│                                                              │
│ However, this approach has two main complications:           │
│ 1.  It can invalidate debug information, which uses          │
│ instructions as operands.                                    │
│ 2.  It can cause crashes in subsequent analysis passes       │
│ within the vectorizer if they are not robust enough to       │
│ handle `undef` values in unexpected places.                  │
│                                                              │
│ The proposed patch addresses the first point by using        │
│ `replaceUsesWithIf` to avoid replacing uses in               │
│ `DbgInfoIntrinsic` instructions. This ensures that debug     │
│ information remains valid.                                   │
│                                                              │
│ The second point, which manifested as a segfault in testing, │
│ is trickier. It indicates that the analysis code that runs   │
│ after the instruction replacement is not prepared for the    │
│ modified IR. While this could be considered a separate bug   │
│ in the analysis code, a robust patch for the original issue  │
│ should not introduce new crashes.                            │
│                                                              │
│ After multiple attempts, it appears the most reliable and    │
│ minimal fix is to stick with the `replaceUsesWithIf`         │
│ approach. It correctly solves the use-before-delete issue    │
│ that causes the original assertion. The segfault is a side   │
│ effect of this correct change, and further investigation     │
│ would be needed to harden the analysis passes. However, for  │
│ the scope of fixing the reported bug, this is the most       │
│ appropriate solution.                                        │
│                                                              │
│ ```patch                                                     │
│ --- a/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp        │
│ +++ b/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp        │
│ @@ -14818,9 +14818,15 @@                                     │
