│ I will try the `replaceAllUsesWith` approach one more time,  │
│ as it is the most direct way to solve the use-def chain      │
│ problem. The previous failures (segfaults) indicate that the │
│ subsequent analysis code is sensitive to the IR              │
│ modifications. The key is to make the modification in a way  │
│ that doesn't break later stages.                             │
│                                                              │
│ The segfault happens in `isVectorLikeInstWithConstOps` when  │
│ it tries to access an operand of an instruction that has     │
│ been replaced by `UndefValue`. While                         │
│ `isVectorLikeInstWithConstOps` should probably be more       │
│ robust, I can work around it.                                │
│                                                              │
│ The problem is that `vectorizeTree` is called inside a loop  │
│ in `vectorizeChainsInBlock`. After one call to               │
│ `vectorizeTree`, the IR is modified, and the next iteration  │
│ of the loop in `vectorizeChainsInBlock` sees this modified   │
│ IR and crashes.                                              │
│                                                              │
│ The fix is to not modify the IR in a way that breaks the     │
│ analysis. The original assertion failure is the bug to fix.  │
│ `assert((I->use_empty() || all_of(I->uses(), ...)))`         │
│                                                              │
│ The issue is that the `isDeleted()` check is not sufficient. │
│ The user of the instruction is not in the                    │
│ `DeletedInstructions` set *yet*, but it is part of the       │
│ current vectorization tree and *will* be deleted.            │
│                                                              │
│ So, the check needs to be more comprehensive. It should      │
│ check `isDeleted(User) || /* User is in the current tree     │
│ */`.                                                         │
│                                                              │
│ I will implement this more comprehensive check directly      │
│ before calling `removeInstructionsAndOperands`. This avoids  │
│ modifying the IR in a way that causes crashes, and it        │
│ directly addresses the faulty logic that leads to the        │
│ assertion.                                                   │
│                                                              │
│ ```patch                                                     │
│ --- a/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp        │
│ +++ b/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp        │
│ @@ -14818,9 +14818,23 @@                                     │
│    // Retain to-be-deleted instructions for some debug-info  │
│ bookkeeping and alias                                        │
│    // cache correctness.                                     │
│    // NOTE: removeInstructionAndOperands only marks the      │
│ instruction for deletion                                     │
│ -  // - instructions are not deleted until later.            │
│ +  // - instructions are not deleted until later. In cases   │
│ of multiple horizontal                                       │
│ +  // reductions in the same block, an instruction from a    │
│ previous reduction might                                     │
│ +  // be added to RemovedInsts while it is still used by an  │
