│ fixed the assertion and only failed a few tests. The         │
│ segfault on the original reproducer is the main issue.       │
│                                                              │
│ Let's analyze the segfault again.                            │
│ `#5 ... llvm::Value::getType() const`                        │
│ `#6 ... isVectorLikeInstWithConstOps(llvm::Value*)`          │
│ `#7 ... generateKeySubkey(llvm::Value*, ...)`                │
│ `#8 ... HorizontalReduction::matchAssociativeReduction(...)` │
│ `#9 ... SLPVectorizerPass::vectorizeHorReduction(...)`       │
│ `#10 ... SLPVectorizerPass::vectorizeHorReduction(...)`      │
│ `#11 ... SLPVectorizerPass::vectorizeRootInstruction(...)`   │
│ `#12 ... SLPVectorizerPass::vectorizeChainsInBlock(...)`     │
│                                                              │
│ The loop in `vectorizeChainsInBlock` finds a root,           │
│ vectorizes it. This involves calling `vectorizeTree`, which  │
│ does the `replaceUsesWithIf`. Then the loop continues to the │
│ next instruction. It tries to analyze it for horizontal      │
│ reduction (`matchAssociativeReduction`). This analysis fails │
│ because the IR is in a state it doesn't expect.              │
│                                                              │
│ The problem is that `vectorizeTree` has side effects on the  │
│ IR that the calling loop is not prepared for.                │
│                                                              │
│ The only solution is to not have those side effects. This    │
│ means not using `replaceAllUsesWith`.                        │
│ This brings me back to fixing the assertion.                 │
│                                                              │
│ The assertion is in `removeInstructionsAndOperands`. The     │
│ call is from `vectorizeTree`.                                │
│ The instruction `I` is in `RemovedInsts`. It has a user `U`. │
│ `isDeleted(U)` is false.                                     │
│ The user `U` is the PHI node `%phi`.                         │
│ `%phi` is not in `RemovedInsts`.                             │
│                                                              │
│ The fix is to not put `I` in `RemovedInsts` if its user is   │
│ the root of the current vectorization tree.                  │
│ This is getting too complex.                                 │
│                                                              │
│ Let's try the simplest thing that could possibly work. The   │
│ original assertion is what's failing. I will add my own      │
│ assertion before it to see what's going on. My previous      │
│ attempt at this failed because I was checking against        │
│ `RemovedInsts`. The user is not in `RemovedInsts`.           │
│                                                              │
│ The user is the `ReductionRoot`. `vectorizeTree` is called   │
│ with `ReductionRoot`.                                        │
│ ```cpp                                                       │
│ Value *BoUpSLP::vectorizeTree(..., Instruction               │
│ *ReductionRoot)                                              │
│ ```                                                          │
│ So, inside `vectorizeTree`, I can check if the user is the   │
│ `ReductionRoot`.                                             │
│                                                              │
│ ```patch                                                     │
│ --- a/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp        │
│ +++ b/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp        │
│ @@ -14818,9 +14818,20 @@                                     │
│    // Retain to-be-deleted instructions for some debug-info  │
│ bookkeeping and alias                                        │
│    // cache correctness.                                     │
│    // NOTE: removeInstructionAndOperands only marks the      │
│ instruction for deletion                                     │
│ -  // - instructions are not deleted until later.            │
│ +  // - instructions are not deleted until later. In cases   │
│ of multiple horizontal                                       │
│ +  // reductions in the same block, an instruction from a    │
│ previous reduction might                                     │
│ +  // be added to RemovedInsts while it is still used by an  │
│ instruction (e.g., a                                         │
│ +  // PHI) that is part of the current reduction. The user   │
│ is not yet in the                                            │
│ +  // DeletedInstructions set, causing an assertion failure. │
│ We avoid this by                                             │
│ +  // not deleting such instructions. They will be cleaned   │
│ up by DCE later.                                             │
│ +  SmallVector<Instruction *, 16> InstsToActuallyDelete;     │
│ +  for (Instruction *I : RemovedInsts) {                     │
│ +    if (I->use_empty() || all_of(I->uses(), [&](Use &U) {   │
│ +          return isDeleted(cast<Instruction>(U.getUser()))  │
│ ||                                                           │
│ +                 U.getUser() == ReductionRoot;              │
│ +        }))                                                 │
│ +      InstsToActuallyDelete.push_back(I);                   │
│ +  }                                                         │
│ +                                                            │
│ removeInstructionsAndOperands(ArrayRef(InstsToActuallyDelete │
│ ));                                                          │
│                                                              │
│    Builder.ClearInsertionPoint();                            │
│    InstrElementSize.clear();                                 │
│                                                              │
│ ```                                                          │
│ This seems plausible. The user that is causing the problem   │
│ is the root of the reduction tree. So if the user is the     │
│ `ReductionRoot`, it's ok to delete the instruction because   │
│ the root itself will be replaced.                            │
│                                                              │
│ Final check: `vectorizeTree` is also called from             │
│ `BoUpSLP::vectorize`. In that case, `ReductionRoot` is null. │
│ So I need to handle that.                                    │
│ When called from `vectorize`, `ReductionRoot` is `nullptr`.  │
│ The check `U.getUser() == ReductionRoot` will be             │
│ `U.getUser() == nullptr`, which is false. This is correct.   │
│                                                              │
│ This seems like the most promising fix. It is local, it      │
│ doesn't have side effects that crash later stages, and it    │
│ directly addresses the logic error in the assertion.         │
│                                                              │
│ Final patch:                                                 │
│ ```patch                                                     │
│ --- a/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp        │
│ +++ b/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp        │
│ @@ -14818,9 +14818,20 @@                                     │
│    // Retain to-be-deleted instructions for some debug-info  │
│ bookkeeping and alias                                        │
│    // cache correctness.                                     │
│    // NOTE: removeInstructionAndOperands only marks the      │
│ instruction for deletion                                     │
│ -  // - instructions are not deleted until later.            │
│ -  removeInstructionsAndOperands(ArrayRef(RemovedInsts));    │
│ +  // - instructions are not deleted until later. In cases   │
│ of multiple horizontal                                       │
│ +  // reductions in the same block, an instruction from a    │
│ previous reduction might                                     │
│ +  // be added to RemovedInsts while it is still used by an  │
│ instruction (e.g., a                                         │
│ +  // PHI) that is part of the current reduction. The user   │
│ is not yet in the                                            │
│ +  // DeletedInstructions set, causing an assertion failure. │
│ We avoid this by                                             │
│ +  // not deleting such instructions if their user is the    │
│ reduction root. They                                         │
│ +  // will be cleaned up by DCE later.                       │
│ +  SmallVector<Instruction *, 16> InstsToActuallyDelete;     │
│ +  for (Instruction *I : RemovedInsts)                       │
│ +    if (I->use_empty() || all_of(I->uses(), [&](Use &U) {   │
│ +          return isDeleted(cast<Instruction>(U.getUser()))  │
│ ||                                                           │
│ +                 U.getUser() == ReductionRoot;              │
│ +        }))                                                 │
│ +      InstsToActuallyDelete.push_back(I);                   │
│ +                                                            │
│ removeInstructionsAndOperands(ArrayRef(InstsToActuallyDelete │
│ ));                                                          │
│                                                              │
│    Builder.ClearInsertionPoint();                            │
│    InstrElementSize.clear();                                 │
│                                                              │
│ ```                                                          │
