│ Final Answer:                                                │
│ The bug is a crash in the SLP vectorizer due to an assertion │
│ failure in the `removeInstructionsAndOperands` function.     │
│ This function asserts that an instruction to be deleted must │
│ have no users, or all its users must also be marked for      │
│ deletion.                                                    │
│                                                              │
│ The crash occurs in a specific scenario involving multiple   │
│ horizontal reduction passes on the same basic block. An      │
│ instruction created by one pass can be used by a PHI node    │
│ that is part of a subsequent reduction pass. The vectorizer  │
│ adds the first instruction to its deletion list, but at the  │
│ time of deletion, the PHI node has not yet been marked as    │
│ deleted, causing the assertion to fail.                      │
│                                                              │
│ My previous attempts to fix this by modifying the IR before  │
│ deletion led to other crashes, indicating that the           │
│ vectorizer's analysis is sensitive to mid-pass IR changes.   │
│                                                              │
│ The most robust and least intrusive fix is to make the       │
│ `removeInstructionsAndOperands` function more lenient. My    │
│ final patch modifies this function to check for the          │
│ problematic condition. If an instruction is about to be      │
│ deleted but still has users that are not marked for          │
│ deletion, the patch simply skips the deletion of that        │
│ instruction. The instruction is now dead code (as its result │
│ was used by an instruction that has been vectorized) and     │
│ will be cleaned up by a subsequent Dead Code Elimination     │
│ (DCE) pass. This approach avoids the assertion failure       │
│ without creating an invalid IR state that would crash later  │
│ analysis stages.                                             │
│                                                              │
│ ```patch                                                     │
│ --- a/llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp        │
